<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06100009 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06100009 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  The Pulitzer Prize winners are not to be revealed until later today, but wordleaked out Monday that Neil Simon reportedly had won the 1991 award for hisnewest Broadway hit, &quot;Lost in Yonkers.&quot; The play stars Irene Worth andMercedes Ruehl. A public relations spokeswoman, who made the announcement,said she got the information from the playwright's wife, Diane.;    (check)Sometime in the next few days, &quot;Home Alone&quot; will replace &quot;Jaws&quot; to become thefourth-highest-grossing movie in the United States, but it won't be fourthvery long. Within another week to 10 days, if tickets sell the way they havebeen selling, the John Hughes film will overtake &quot;Return of the Jedi&quot; tobecome No. 3.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  ALSO NOTED . . .  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  People  </MEMO><TEXT>     (check) Dr. Christian Barnard, who performed the world's first hearttransplant, plans to leave South Africa because of growing political unrest,the Star newspaper reported Monday. Barnard performed the first hearttransplant in 1967.;    (check) Architect Robert Venturi, whose writings andbuildings sparked the reintroduction of decoration and historical elements inarchitecture, is winner of the 1991 Pritzker Architecture Prize, the leadinginternational award in its field.;    (check) Jeffrey Tate is resigning asprincipal conductor of the Royal Opera for a similar post at the RotterdamPhilharmonic Orchestra, the Royal Opera says. No successor was announced.;   (check) The weekend sale of 33 Arabian horses owned by entertainer WayneNewton brought $206,250, representatives of New York-based Sotheby's reportedMonday.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Information in this column if from Mercury News wire services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910409  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY